ce:section.ce:para:
To better illustrate the photocatalytic mechanism, Mott-Schottky experiment was respectively conducted on CN and Mo2C in 0.5 M Na2SO4 solution to evaluate the band positions of the as-prepared catalysts then to estimate the flat band potential (Efb). As presented in Fig. S10A and B, the Mott-Schottky plots of CN and Mo2C both show positive slopes, corresponding to n-type semiconducting properties with Efb at about −1.61 and −0.23 V vs. Ag/AgCl, which can be calculated to be −1.41 and −0.03 V vs normal hydrogen electrode (NHE), respectively [83]. Generally, the conduction band (CB) potential for n-type semiconductor is considered to be more negative than that of Efb by about −0.1 or −0.2 V; therefore, the CB edge potentials of CN and Mo2C were determined to be −1.61 and −0.23 V vs. NHE, respectively [84]. Besides, the band gap (Eg
                        ) values of CN and Mo2C were estimated by fitting the optical transition at the absorption edges using the Tauc/David-Mott model. Fig. S10C and D indicate that the Eg
                         values of g-C3N4 and Mo2C are 2.90 and 1.24 eV vs. NHE, respectively. As a result, the valence band (VB) potentials of CN and Mo2C can be calculated to be 1.01 and 1.29 V vs. NHE, respectively.
